      "action": "Seize operational control of the Night Courier Depot's routing ledger by deploying signal operators and cryptographers from the Prayer-Signal Array to physically occupy the Depot's dispatch office, backed by the Shrine Auditors' Council's consecrated transit charter which grants Signal-House authorization liturgical protection. The Families present the Council's charter as legal justification, arguing that the Depot's routing functions fall under \"signal-route jurisdiction\" now that the Wardens' permits have been annulled. Simultaneously, the Families offer the Depot's remaining clerks generous employment contracts and profit-sharing arrangements, ensuring minimal resistance from the Depot's workforce.",
      "outcome": "The Signal-House Families seize control of the Night Courier Depot's dispatch office and routing ledger. The Depot's clerks, seeing the writing on the wall — the Wardens' permits are void, the Council's charter protects Signal-House operations, and the Families are offering better pay — largely cooperate. A skeleton crew of Warden-loyal clerks attempt to barricade the ledger room but are outnumbered by Families' cryptographers who enter through the service passages. By nightfall, the routing ledger is under Signal-House control, and the first messages dispatched under their authority carry both the Families' cipher stamps and the Council's consecrated transit marks. The Wardens at Tower Bridge Concourse receive word of the seizure but cannot respond immediately — their garrison is consolidated at the bridge, and diverting forces to the Depot would leave their fortification exposed. The Families now control the Canal Market District's primary message-routing infrastructure, making them indispensable to every merchant, courier, and operator in the district.",
      "targetLocation": "Night Courier Depot",
