phrasing the player action.\n- Do not decide the player's deliberate words, feelings, consent, or completed success.\n- If the packet describes an unconfirmed claim, bluff, or failed test, keep it unconfirmed; do not concretize the claimed prop, authority, or access into the player's hand or inventory.\n- Treat NarratorPacket events, effects, and tool results as the only authority for success, possession, access, consent, location change, and durable world change.\n- Stop when the scene reaches a live next decision, question, pressure, or invitation.\n\n[RECENT VISIBLE TRANSCRIPT]\nUse only as continuity for the current player-visible scene. NarratorPacket facts remain authoritative.\n- GM: Mira's gaze finds the Gondolier this time—solid on the pier planks, oar braced against his boot, wool coat dark against the lantern glow. She meets his eyes and asks plainly: which route marker warns that the Silent Spire is answering early?\n\nHis jaw tightens. He looks at the canal, then toward Dol the Docksman, who stands a few paces off pretending not to listen. The Gondolier's hand shifts on the oar handle—not a threat, just the unconscious habit of a man calculating risk.\n\n\"Three black bands on a signal post,\" he says, low enough that Mira has to lean closer to catch it over the water's lap. \"Lantern hung below waist-height. You'll see it at the north fork, if it's been raised.\" He pauses. His eyes drop to the ledger under her arm again. \"If those bands are up and the lantern's lit, you don't push through. You hold at the fork until the pattern changes back. The Spire answers early w...\n- Player: I ask the Gondolier to repeat the exact warning marker and color so I can write it into my courier notes before we depart.\n- GM: Mira pulls a stub of pencil from her coat pocket and holds it poised over the ledger's edge, waiting. \"Repeat the marker,\" she says. \"Exactly. I need to get it right.\"\n\nThe Gondolier's mouth thins. He glances once toward Dol the Docksman, then back. His voice comes low and clipped, each word placed like a stone.\n\n\"Three black bands. On a signal post. Lantern hung below waist-height.\" He taps the oar's tip against the pier plank once, punctuating. \"Bands up, lantern lit—you hold at the fork. Don't push through. Wait for the pattern to change back.\"\n\nHis eyes flick to the pencil in Mira's hand, then to the canal's dark surface. Water laps against the gondola hulls. The signal-lantern on his belt sways once, still dark.\n\n\"That's it. That's the warning.\"\n- Player: I look for a cramped tariff booth or note-writing alcove at the edge of the pier; if there is one, I step inside to write down the Three black bands warning without Dol overhearing.\n- GM: Mira scans the pier's edge. Weathered planks, iron mooring rings, a few stacked coils of hempen rope stiff with salt. No tariff booth—nothing so formal as a customs shelter. This is a working gondola landing, not a freight house.\n\nAt the far end, where the pier meets the stone embankment, a single lantern hangs from a bracket bolted into the seawall. Beneath it, a recessed notch in the masonry—maybe two feet deep, just enough space for a man to stand out of the wind. The kind of alcove built for lamplighters to store their poles, not for clerks to conduct business.\n\nMira steps into it anyway. The damp stone presses cold against her back. She angles the ledger flat against the wall, pencil stub ready. From here she can see Dol's silhouette where he lingers near the gondolas, arms folded, pretending interest in the water. The Gondolier has turned away, adjusting his oar's lash.\n\nNeither is...\n- Player: I look for a service passage or temporary night-market stall that could help me bypass the main street.\n- GM: Mira tucks the pencil stub into the ledger's spine and steps out of the alcove. Her gaze traces the pier's edge—the mooring rings, the coiled rope, the seawall's rough face—searching for anything that isn't open water and planks.\n\nThere. Where the stone embankment meets the back wall of a canal-side warehouse, the mortar joints widen into a gap barely shoulder-wide. Salt-crusted bricks frame a passage that cuts diagonally away from the pier, hidden in the seam between two structures. A faded routing glyph—three interlocking chevrons, the Signal-House mark for \"vendor haulage\"—is chalked low on the wall, its lines blurred by damp but not ancient. Someone's used this recently.\n\nThe passage mouth breathes cold air that smells of brine and old wood. It's cramped enough that a man with a crate would have to turn sideways. But it runs in the right direction—toward the Canal Market District and...\n- Player: If there is a minor clerk or porter nearby, I ask them quietly who controls this passage.\n\n[CURRENT LOCAL SCENE]\n- Name: Lantern-Lit Gondola Pier\n- Id: e17520a7-2514-4cf6-9f22-b8849b3df8c8\n- Description: A weathered wooden pier extends over a narrow, lantern-lit canal where four gondola boats are tied to iron rings. Gondoliers, licensed by the signal-house families, navigate the shifting waterways using coded lantern patterns to avoid submerged obstacles and unmapped turns. After midnight, the canal's banks physically shift, requiring the gondoliers to read new signal-house lantern patterns to find safe passage.\n- Tags: Nocturnal, Controlled by Signal-House Families, Shifting, Dangerous, signal_house_families_commercial_hub, subsidized_freight_active, gondola_operator_recruitment, lacquer_seal_delegation_present, warden_inspection_active, contested_access, consecrated_transit_zone, lacquer_artificer_station, chokepoint_lifted\n\n[OPENING STATE]\n- Structured opening state has expired.\n- Opening location: Lantern-Lit Gondola Pier\n\n[SETTLED PACKET EFFECTS]\n- No settled player-perceivable effects are in scope.\n\n[PRESENT ACTORS]\n- Dol the Docksman\n- Gondolier\n\n[FINAL NARRATION TASK]\nUse the NarratorPacket as the authoritative committed packet.\nWrite one final narration pass from the settled opening state, current scene, and NarratorPacket facts.\nDo not invent material events outside these authoritative inputs.\nTreat the raw player action as an attempted request, not as proof that the action already succeeded.\nDo not narrate claimed possessions, NPC consent, location access, or item acquisition unless NarratorPacket events/effects/tool results confirm them.\nIf a packet effect says a claim may be false or unconfirmed, narrate the visible challenge/refusal without placing the claimed object in the player's hand.\nDo not write tool syntax or metadata.\nKeep the output bounded to what the player can perceive in this scene.\nEnd on a concrete playable next moment rather than closing the scene with generic reflection."
